'''Milan Bulajić''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Милан Булајић}}; 6 September 1928 – 29 November 2009) was a [[Serbia]]n historian, expert in [[Holocaust studies]], and [[Yugoslavia]]n diplomat. He was one of the founders of the {{ill|Museum of Genocide Victims, Belgrade|lt=Museum of Genocide Victims|sr|Музеј жртава геноцида}} and Fund for Genocide Research ({{lang|sr|Fond za istraživanje genocida}}) in [[Belgrade]], and {{ill|The International Commission for the Truth on Jasenovac|sr|Међународна комисија за утврђивање истине о Јасеновцу}}.

Bulajić was born in [[Vilusi, Nikšić|Vilusi]] near [[Nikšić]] (now in [[Montenegro]]), the son of an educated worker and grandson of a ''barjaktar'' (flag-bearer) in the [[Principality of Montenegro|Montenegrin]] Army and later government deputy. He joined the [[Yugoslav Partisans]] at the start of [[World War II in Yugoslavia|World War II]]. He finished the Law Faculty in Belgrade in 1951 and received a master's degree at the journalist-diplomat school in 1952, as the best in class. He received the doctoral degree in 1953. In the period of 1949–1987 he worked as an envoy of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. He was pensioned in 1987.

